ody":"<p>To make this derivation, it is better to focus on the <em>population size<\/em> of a strategy as opposed to the <em>frequency<\/em> of a strategy. Let $N_i$ be the population size of the strategy $i$. Populations in this model grows exponentially; i.e., $\\Delta N_i = f_i N_i$. The equation for continuous exponential growth is $\\dot N_i = f_i N_i$. Since $x_i=N_i/N$ and $\\dot N = \\bar f N$, calculating $\\dot x_i$ by using the quotient rule gives us the continuous replicator eqn.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40113,"question_id":40103,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1446302026}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40103/discrete-vs-continuous-replicator-dynamics","last_activity_date":1446302026,"creation_date":1446229609,"answer_count":1,"title":"Discrete vs Continuous Replicator Dynamics","body":"<p>The replicator eqn in the case of discrete non-overlapping generations and asexual reproduction is given by the <strong>discrete<\/strong> replicator eqn:\n$$x_i(t+1) = x_i (t)\\frac{f_i(t)}{\\bar f (t)}$$\nwhere $x_i$ is the frequency of the strategy $i$ and each individual playing strategy $i$ produces $f_i$ copies of itself in the next generation. $\\bar f$ is the average fitness. Thus\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Delta x_i = x_i(t) \\frac{(f_i(t) - \\bar f (t))}{\\bar f (t)}\n\\end{equation}\nIn the case in which $x_i$ is a continuous variable, we have the <strong>continuous<\/strong> replicator eqn given by\n$$\\dot x_i = x_i (f_i - \\bar f)$$<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Question:<\/strong> I suppose we should be able to derive the continuous replicator eqn from the discrete replicator eqn by evaluating the discrete replicator eqn for $\\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0}$. How can I do this derivation?<\/p>\n","question_id":40103,"tags":["evolution","natural-selection","theoretical-biology","evolutionary-game-theory"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":40113,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":72,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4afbddf8c56459e93789b4d8d2d06c9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19745,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19745/bob","reputation":21,"display_name":"Bob"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":40126,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446280999,"comment_id":67373,"body":"Welcome to Biology. Could you tell us where you got this information from? It&#39;s interesting, though, given that one lung is larger than the other."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/m27DI.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14852,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14852/talha-irfan","reputation":275,"display_name":"Talha Irfan","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":40126,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446296229,"comment_id":67376,"body":"@AliceD And if I am not wrong, its true for our feet as well?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SGxqm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18860,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18860/harry-vervet","reputation":1769,"display_name":"Harry Vervet"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446300149,"creation_date":1446300149,"body":"<p>I would strongly question whether the underlying claim that testicular asymmetry is <em>generally<\/em> true. While there is no known clinical significance of testicular asymmetry, most men probably have no noticable difference in testicular size. There have been a number of studies over several decades, and findings have been inconsistent.<\/p>\n\n<p>Braus (1956) stated that the left testis was heavier and lower; <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1244352/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Chang et al. (1960)<\/a> determined on study of cadavers that the right testis was generally larger than the left.<\/p>\n\n<p>A <a href=\"http://humrep.oxfordjournals.org/content/23/4/792.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">2008 study<\/a> in 0 to 6-year-old boys found no difference in testicular volume measured ultrasonographically.<\/p>\n\n<p>Age or level of sexual activity may also play a role; it is known that testes get larger during sexual activity.<\/p>\n\n<p>The reason for testicular asymmetry is unknown. It has been reported in many different species (see <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9639153\" rel=\"nofollow\">Yu, 1998<\/a>). The most common explanation provided in humans is that the right testis is more commonly larger than the left due to a difference in vascular anatomy: the left testicular vein empties into the renal vein while the right testicular vein empties into the inferior vena cava. However, anatomy alone would not explain testicular asymmetry in other species as well, so there is no doubt more to this than presently understood.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40132,"question_id":40126,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40126/why-is-one-testicle-larger-than-the-other","last_activity_date":1446300149,"creation_date":1446279575,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is one testicle larger than the other?","body":"<p>Why is one testicle generally larger in humans? Just due to asymmetric development, or is there a hypothesis as to some utility it serves? I read that the different heights may be attributed to attempting to keep them from hitting against one another. Is there a similar guess to the purpose for the difference in sizes?<\/p>\n","question_id":40126,"tags":["human-biology","human-anatomy"],"sc