ers already given.<\/p>\n\n<p>In terms of views on ageing, there's evidence to support both:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>general principles that may apply to it; and <\/li>\n<li>it being a consequence of a collection of degenerative processes (this is apparently the more supported view).<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Since almost all biological systems in the body degenerates with age and this happens seemingly at random, it's been difficult to identify particular catalysts that cause this. Consequently, biologists apparently steer away from a general theory or mechanism.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, there are two classes of theories that have been floating around. That is 'loose cannon' and 'weak link'.<\/p>\n\n<p><em>Loose Cannon<\/em> encompasses theories that support the 'wear and tear' proposition. Two popular theories under this banner are <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1383768\" rel=\"nofollow\">free radicals<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.springerlink.com/content/qq764j6548k56266/\" rel=\"nofollow\">glucose<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><em>Weak Link<\/em> suggests that particular physiological systems are vulnerable during senescence and if a system fails, the whole body begins to decline. It's suggested that the neuroendocrine and immune systems are particularly vulnerable. <\/p>\n\n<p>There is also a limit on the ability of cells to replicate - this is called the Hayflick Phenomenon (or limit). The reduction of the enzyme <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1933587/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Telomerase<\/a>, which lengthens telomeres during mitosis, is implicated in limiting a cell's ability to replicate indefinitely.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1549,"question_id":344,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b9ab37a714c62cfdc39c2c57601c2cee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1067,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1067/c0zmic","reputation":162,"display_name":"c0zmic"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1340785194,"creation_date":1340785194,"body":"<p>\"WHY\" we age is a different question from \"HOW\" we age.  The \"WHY\" refers to ageing from an evolutionally standpoint, whereas the \"HOW\" refers to biology of ageing.  As for the \"WHY\" I would read a few papers on the antagonistic pleiotropy hypothesis (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22329645\" rel=\"nofollow\">click here<\/a>).  As for the \"HOW\", there is no definitive understanding of mechanisms of ageing.  However, the role of cellular senescence in ageing and age-related disease is a major player in the biology of ageing (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19234764\" rel=\"nofollow\">click here<\/a> for example).  When cells become senescent (due to either telomere shortening/DNA-damage) they can no longer divide to regenerate damaged tissue.  Additionally, senescent cells are highly pro-inflammatory and so have the potential to damage the surrounding tissue if the are not removed.  In younger organisms, senescent cells are most likely removed my the immune system, but as organisms age, the immune system also ages and can no longer effectively remove senescent cells.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2764,"question_id":344,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"score":0,"post_id":2789,"edited":false,"creation_date":1341061793,"comment_id":4007,"body":"Interesting, but the Guardian article is not really a reference - better to go to the original  paper. Also, a concern with telomere-lenghtening strategies would be carncer surely."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":2789,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"edited":false,"creation_date":1341066942,"comment_id":4008,"body":"cancer is mentioned in the article..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ea215e4766bf229b50b8791e2e03776d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3894,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3894/ducfabulous","reputation":180,"display_name":"DucFabulous","accept_rate":42},"score":0,"post_id":2789,"edited":false,"creation_date":1373289503,"comment_id":11900,"body":"I was think about this. I have same idea, so i think to be immortal we should resolve cancer first. So i&#39;m still researching about cancer..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":2789,"edited":false,"creation_date":1373317105,"comment_id":11917,"body":"are you aware of Aubrey De Gray?  His thinking is theoretical at this point, but well articulated. <a href=\"http://www.ted.com/talks/aubrey_de_grey_says_we_can_avoid_aging.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">ted.com/talks/aubrey_de_grey_says_we_can_avoid_aging.html<\/a>"}],"down_v