se,"creation_date":1336384524,"comment_id":2851,"body":"Yes, I read it: &quot;The gonads are testes regardless of phenotype due to the influence of the Y-chromosome. A 46,XY female thus does not have ovaries or a uterus, and can neither contribute an egg towards conception nor gestate a child.&quot; This means that if you have XY chromosomes, you will never be a normal woman, even if you insensitive to androgens."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/99716e02429624201ec8f85f820a81ce?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19423,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19423/mars","reputation":198,"display_name":"Mars"},"score":0,"post_id":2102,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446097090,"comment_id":67210,"body":"That the female form is the default, and that there&#39;s no selection for removing some default trait, isn&#39;t enough to explain male nipples without  more information about the developmental sequence.  If nipples developed late in the process after sex determination, then the default status of female traits would be irrelevant to male nipples.  So the hypothesis should include the suggestion that nipples arise early in development.  Another possibility is that, regardless of what sex is the default, nipples are <a href=\"http://philpapers.org/rec/SCHGEA\" rel=\"nofollow\">generatively entrenched<\/a>."}],"down_vote_count":7,"last_activity_date":1336114232,"creation_date":1336114232,"body":"<p>I believe it is for this reason: the female body plan is the default one. Males are a variation upon that, in humans at least. Nipples are part of the basic body plan. For a man to <em>not<\/em> have them, he would need to actively evolve something that would prevent nipples from developing. There is no selective pressure for the development of such a thing, so it hasn't happened. Keep in mind that the code for the general body plan is shared between males and females. The Y chromosome modifies the development of that body plan so the person becomes male.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2102,"question_id":2073,"up_vote_count":33},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e6a63597e64ab3951e140d4cc4dae4f8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":938,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/938/jds","reputation":393,"display_name":"jds"},"score":17,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9fca3702076c969eb513703a020c7db?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":510,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/510/preece","reputation":1144,"display_name":"Preece"},"score":0,"post_id":2429,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b219b646efa3c74061977c39306c1841?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":810,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/810/shep","reputation":1198,"display_name":"Shep","accept_rate":67},"edited":false,"creation_date":1338816923,"comment_id":3428,"body":"@Shep And yet it misses the most crucial piece of information, while simply restating other things that have been said. In fact, his second point is almost an exact restatement of something I said. The female body plan is the default one, and that fact is the heart of a real answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/166093d036b7185b3a53052889d99e47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1472,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1472/mew","reputation":836,"display_name":"Mew","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"post_id":2429,"edited":false,"creation_date":1357567741,"comment_id":8184,"body":"No Preece, it is not saying the female body plan is the default one.  It is saying that if a trait is necessary for one gender, it is simpler to have it for both genders as well, unless it hinders the gender that doesnt&#39; require it."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":3,"post_id":2429,"edited":false,"creation_date":1422834111,"comment_id":46199,"body":"I agree that males probably have nipples just because there is positive selection in females for having nipples while it is neutral in males (there is gender specific selection coefficient for having nipples). However, this is not exactly what the Neutral Theory of Evolution states! This is probably why no one mentioned the Neutral Theory of Evolution. Therefore, the answer seems a bit misleading."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"post_id":2429,"edited":false,"creation_date":1422834195,"comment_id":46200,"body":"Also, the sentence <code>mutations that are not necessarily motivated by increased &quot;fitness&quot;<\/code> should better be replaced by <code>the existence of alleles present at high frequency even though they don&#39;t confer a selective advantage (that is, they don&#39;t confer higher fitness to the carrier)<\/code>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/FxxEx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13072,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13072/corvus","reputation":1501,"display_name":"Corvus"},"score":5,"post_id":2429,"edited":false,"creation_date":1431324724,"comment_id":54512,"body":"I&#39;m astonished that this answer has 20 upvotes and was accepted. The correct answer to this question has <i>nothing<\/i> to do with the neutral theory of evolution (which, as Remy notes, is not the same as observing that some traits are neutral) and everything to do evolutionary constraint (in this case, with the timing of sex determination in the developing embryo)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":3,"post_id":2429,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445364334,"comment_id":66740,"body":"This answer is wrong. The most active users of Biology.SE are considering the problem <a href=\"http://meta.biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3189/how-to-deal-with-a-wrong-answer-that-received-many-upvotes/3191?noredirect=1#comment3559_3191\">here<\/a>."}],"down_vote_count":9,"last_activity_date":1340049916,"creation_date":1338385199,"body":"<p>No one has mentioned the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutral_theory_of_molecular_evolution\">Neutral Theory of Evolution<\/a>, which explains mutations that are not necessarily motivated by increased \"fitness\". <\/p>\n\n<p>Similarly (and more to the point for this question) there is no selective pressure with regards to mens nipples. <\/p>\n\n<p>Men have nipples because they find a purpose on women, but for men there is no reason to not have them. From an evolutionary stand point it is simpler for men to have them. The more complex situation (Women have nipples but men do not) would most likely only occur if there was some selective pressure for men to not have nipples. <\/p>\n","answer_id":2429,"question_id":2073,"up_vote_count":26,"last_edit_date":1340049916},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oOxxZ.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13297,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13297/axsvl77","reputation":119,"display_name":"axsvl77"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b219b646efa3c74061977c39306c1841?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":810,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/810/shep","reputation":1198,"display_name":"Shep","accept_rate":67},"score":2,"post_id":