 is sort of <a href=\"http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/strange-but-true-males-can-lactate/\" rel=\"nofollow\">common knowledge<\/a>. I heard about it at a <a href=\"http://www.llli.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Le Leche Leage<\/a> meeting when my son was small. <\/p>\n\n<p>This question could even be considered culturally <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/blogs/richard-banks/can-men-breastfeed\" rel=\"nofollow\">biased<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":28248,"question_id":2073,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":18,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446221053,"creation_date":1445266318,"body":"<p>The two key concepts here are <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>sex-specific selection<\/strong>, and the fact that <\/li>\n<li><strong>males and females share the majority of genes<\/strong><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p><strong>1) sex-specific selection<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Obviously any population where females lacked nipples would be in trouble. Men, on the other hand, have no evolutionary need for them, but they don't <em>pay<\/em> much either\u2014there is no strong selection <em>against<\/em> men with nipples. So at first sight, it seems that <em>nipples are positively selected in females while seem to be quite neutral in males<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>2) Males and females share the majority of genes<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>If you consider two separate species where the two species undergo different selection pressures, you will just see one species evolve toward one optima while the other one will independently evolve toward the other optima.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, males and females are not independent entities. The vast majority of our genes can be found in one sex as well as in the other sex. In other words, <strong>male phenotypes do not evolve independently of female phenotypes<\/strong>. As a result of this interdependence, you can end up with the trait that is selected in one sex present in the other sex.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Evolutionary equilibrium<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>This is all much more rigorously defined in terms of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selection_coefficient\" rel=\"nofollow\">selection coefficients<\/a> and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_pressure\" rel=\"nofollow\">evolutionary pressure<\/a>. Without going into the math, the questions of <em>who has the highest selection coefficient<\/em> and <em>How differential is gene expression for this trait<\/em> are important questions to predict the equilibrium trait value in both sexes.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Lack of a strong selection pressure<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Finally, any trait that is seemingly not-useful has to have a significant disadvantage on the fitness of the organism to be selected out (<a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/35532/3340\">If a trait would be advantageous to an organism, why hasn&#39;t it evolved?<\/a>). Even if a trait is useless for both males and females it may persist. The case of females needing the trait just makes its elimination in males even more difficult, as explained above. However, in some mammalian species the males do lack the nipples (<a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/34150/3340\">Evolutionarily, why do male rats and horses lack nipples?<\/a>).<\/p>\n","answer_id":39769,"question_id":2073,"up_vote_count":18,"community_owned_date":1445271243,"last_edit_date":1446221053}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2073/why-do-men-have-nipples","last_activity_date":1446221053,"creation_date":1336023822,"answer_count":4,"title":"Why do men have nipples?","body":"<p>I'd be tempted to call nipples in men vestigial, but that suggests they have no modern function. They <em>do<\/em> have a function, of course, but only in women. So why do <em>men<\/em> (and all male mammals) have them? <\/p>\n","question_id":2073,"tags":["evolution","zoology","genetics"],"score":44,"accepted_answer_id":39769,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1456385926,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2278,"up_vote_count":44,"last_edit_date":1336075225},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/500d7990f4d8c083fac65cfb0514d992?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19587/bryant-keirns","reputation":6,"display_name":"Bryant Keirns"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/986656e4512511a0c55dc91dd218bbeb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18905,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18905/nathan","reputation":1086,"display_name":"Nathan"},"score":0,"post_id":40094,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446215344,"comment_id":67348,"body":"E. faecalis is an aerotolerant anaerobe. It can&#39;t use oxygen but it doesn&#39;t harm it."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e5f813565669b0b078c9e7b5d4172b0f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19454,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19454/atp","reputation":320,"display_name":"ATP"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446219781,"creation_date":1446219781,"body":"<p>E. faecalis is an aerotolerant anaerobe, while E. coli is a facultative anaerobe therefore if in a non-aerobic environment it can switch to anaerobic respiration. E.coli is also capable of fermentation.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is an article for on the various respiratory pathways of E.coli: <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0005272897000340\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0005272897000340<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>One other reasons why cells may grow in a nutrient poor medium is that many types of bacteria have programmed cell death that ultimately is for the better of the entire bacterial population. When nutrients get low some cells commit \"suicide\" and release nutrients to surrounding bacteria. Just an extra thought.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40099,"question_id":40094,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40094/why-would-a-bacterial-population-show-initial-growth-when-it-is-in-unfavorable-g","last_activity_date":1446219781,"creation_date":1446213156,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why would a bacterial population show initial growth when it is in unfavorable growth conditions?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ulTU0.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ulTU0.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This figure shows the anaerobe E. faecalis grown in aerobic conditions, E. coli grown in restricted conditions that are not specified. Why do they show an increase in abundance initially? The black line is growth rate and to me I would think neither would grow at all.<\/p>\n","question_id":40094,"tags":["biochemistry","microbiology","bacteriology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":28,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1hvwh.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19484,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19484/123","reputation":278,"display_name":"123","accept_rate":50},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446216055,"creation_date":1446216055,"body":"<p>Not surprisingly, the WHO has a lot of data, I think especially interesting for you is this interactive figure, which you can find <a href=\"http://gamapserver.who.int/gho/interactive_charts/mbd/life_expectancy/atlas.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qdgjK.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qdgjK.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Other data on this topic can be found on the WHO website <a href=\"http://www.who.int/gho/mortality_burden_disease/life_tables/en/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>, in the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_life_expectancy\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia<\/a> or from the <a href=\"http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.LE00.IN\" rel=\"nofollow\">Worldbank<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40098,"question_id":40097,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40097/where-can-i-find-a-global-life-expectancy-table","last_activity_date":1446216055,"creation_date":1446215442,"answer_count":1,"title":"Where can I find a global life expectancy table?","body":"<p>I've found good information on specific countries and demographics, but I can't seem to find global numbers.  I know that the world life expectancy is around 71.0, but I'm trying to get a percentile breakdown in the form of something like an actuarial life table.<\/p>\n","question_id":40097,"tags":["population-dynamics","population-biology","lifespan"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":18,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2180b15f8ff884930fddb5705669d2b3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19700,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19700/brandon","reputation":6,"display_name":"Brandon"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":40060,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446198152,"comment_id":67319,"body":"Why specifically algal amino acids though?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446214515,"creation_date":1446193178,"body":"<p>E.coli can do that and in fact does this a lot in a commonly used bacterial medium: The popular <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lysogeny_broth\" rel=\"nofollow\">LB Medium<\/a>. This is composed of three components:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tryptone\" rel=\"nofollow\">Tryptone<\/a>, a peptide mix made by digesting milk casein with the peptidase Trypsin (10g/l) <\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yeast_extract\" rel=\"nofollow\">Yeast extract<\/a>, made by autolysis of the cells (5g/l)<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Sodium chloride (10g/l)<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>The original formulation of Bertani from 1951 (see reference 1) also contains 1g/l Glucose, which was later discarded, since the handling is easier without it (glucose cannot be autoclaved as it degrades).<\/p>\n\n<p>Since the medium does not contain any other utilizable sugars as a carbon source, the bacteria use free amino acids (and small peptides up to 650 Da in size) for their growth. The reason for this limit is the exclusion size of the bacterial porin channels which allows the uptake of the peptides and free amino acids (see reference 2 for details).<\/p>\n\n<p>Once these are exhausted, the growth stops, which is the reason why LB Medium is actually not very good suited to get really high densities (that's why SOC media are used for some applications). Read the excellent paper in reference 3 and the also excellent article in reference 4 if you want to know more about the topic.<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't think it matters from which source your amino acids are coming. Regarding the concentration I haven't found any data, but in reference 4 it is estimated that only about 25% can be used by the bacteria. Since the mixture contains about 15 grams of protein lysate, this would roughly mean about 4 grams of free amino acids or more.<\/p>\n\n<p>References:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC386127/?page=1\" rel=\"nofollow\">Studies on Lysogenesis I.<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.jbc.org/content/243/23/6291.abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">Size Restriction on Peptide Utilization in Escherichia coli<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://jb.asm.org/content/189/23/8746.long\" rel=\"nofollow\">Escherichia coli Physiology in Luria-Bertani Broth<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://schaechter.asmblog.org/schaechter/2009/11/the-limitations-of-lb-medium.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Limitations of LB Medium<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":40088,"question_id":40060,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1446214515}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40060/is-it-possible-to-grow-e-coli-k12-with-algal-amino-acids-as-the-sole-carbon-sou","last_activity_date":1446214515,"creation_date":1446133510,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is it possible to grow E. coli K12 with algal amino acids as the sole carbon source?","body":"<p>Instead of glucose or glycerol, is it possible for E coli to grow on an amino acid mixture as the sole carbon source and, if so, what should the concentration be? <\/p>\n","question_id":40060,"tags":["cell-culture","amino-acids","ecoli"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":29,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/9XAjJ.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5963,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5963/harshal-gajjar","reputation":118,"display_name":"Harshal Gajjar"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":15585,"edited":false,"creation_date":1394322966,"comment_id":20957,"body":"A selection of related questions: <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7401/what-makes-a-gene-dominant-or-recessive\">what makes a gene dominant or recessive<\/a>, <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1294/why-some-genes-are-dominant-to-each-other-what-is-the-mechanism-behind-it/1325#1325\">why are some genes dominant to each other?<\/a> and <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2653/relative-property-of-alleles\">relative properties of alleles<\/a>."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79614cc5fcd376b95171a5c8f6354e8a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5754/jarlemag","reputation":3075,"display_name":"jarlemag"},"score":10,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/9XAjJ.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5963,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5963/harshal-gajjar","reputation":118,"display_name":"Harshal Gajjar"},"score":0,"post_id":15586,"edited":false,"creation_date":1394296968,"comment_id":20944,"body":"Yeah, I used wrong term gene over here. Thanks. But question still remains unanswered."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79614cc5fcd376b95171a5c8f6354e8a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5754/jarlemag","reputation":3075,"display_name":"jarlemag"},"score":0,"post_id":15586,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/9XAjJ.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5963,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5963/harshal-gajjar","reputation":118,"displa