reciable different density than one with the tongue in.  Same for retractable limbs (which are generically cool).<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v197/n4863/abs/197179a0.html\">This article<\/a> gives us an estimate for the density of keratin at \"1.283 g/c.c. for cow horn to 1.335 g/c.c. for echidna quill tip\" which putts it solidly more dense than water.  This means we're looking for a small heavily armored mammal, which leads me to suspect the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pangolin\">pangolin<\/a>.  I don't readily know it's density, and I would be fine with others taking the time to calculate it (I'm not interested in getting that specific).<\/p>\n\n<p>I have fewer ideas on which mammals are least dense.  Going by <a href=\"http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/277/1691/2193.full\">this article<\/a> I would guess rodents have the least dense skeletons. In particular I was surprised by this graph:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/iBl44.jpg\" alt=\"comparison of bird, bat, and rodent bone density\"><\/p>\n\n<p>But also don't know that means we should exclude something like a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sperm_whale\">sperm whale<\/a> which has a lot of fat (lower density than water) and has enough lung capacity to dive for hours in deep water.  But on the off chance that the skeletal density is the best bet, I'm going to guess the least dense animal is a rodent, and if I have to pick one species I'm going with the least massive, the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shrew\">shrew<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Doubt any one has really researched the displacement of many of the animals that should be in the running for this, so I'm not convinced a more exact answer could be reached.<\/p>\n","answer_id":20113,"question_id":20072,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1406901830}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/20072/mammal-body-density","last_activity_date":1446089785,"creation_date":1406689796,"answer_count":1,"title":"Mammal body density","body":"<p>Human body density is approximately 1 kg/l (same as fresh water) - which is not surprising (at first) given that we are 70% water, and <em>is<\/em> surprising (on a second thought), given that the other 30% can be just about anything (from the air in the lungs to the relatively heavy bones).<\/p>\n\n<p>How remarkable is that?<\/p>\n\n<p>Consider other mammalian species.\nFor each species, compute the average body density of an adult.\nThus, for each species we have the number - the mean body density.\nHow are these numbers distributed?\nMostly heavier than water? Lighter?<\/p>\n\n<p>It is unlikely that this kind of research has been done, so I would settle for something simpler: what are the densest/lightest mammals? (or, in general, vertebrae)<\/p>\n\n<p>PS. As you can guess, I am a mathematician, not a biologist :-)<\/p>\n\n<p>PPS. Given abundance of water of Earth's surface (70%, same as above!), it makes a lot of sense to be as dense as water: not heavier (to avoid drowning), not lighter (to be able to dive for food), so natural selection should favor the density of 1.  Are there exceptions?<\/p>\n","question_id":20072,"tags":["mammals"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":20113,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":356,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1418671426},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dcad064eef16b5d91a14d8cd6ad936fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19667,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19667/ama","reputation":16,"display_name":"ama"},"closed_date":1446097595,"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dcad064eef16b5d91a14d8cd6ad936fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19667,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19667/ama","reputation":16,"display_name":"ama"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae0014e2b5be5ac76e0892cdd6f72e8e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6289,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6289/l-b","reputation":764,"display_name":"L.B."},"score":1,"post_id":40017,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446062985,"comment_id":67187,"body":"Please do add some solid references."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1446080327,"creation_date":1446035686,"body":"<p>Because the nictitating membrane secretes a fluid that is resistant to evaporation. Therefore, birds need not blink their eyes during flight.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40017,"question_id":40016,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1446080327}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40016/how-can-birds-keep-their-eyes-moist-during-flight","last_activity_date":1446080339,"creation_date":1446031368,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can birds keep their eyes moist during flight?","body":"<p>Mammals have an upper lid and small mass  of tissue in the upper corner known as nictitating membrane. This helps keep the eyes clean; birds can moisten their eyes in flight using this membrane without blinking. How does this work?<\/p>\n","question_id":40016,"tags":["zoology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":false,"view_count":43,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1446080339},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/2zmAC.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9573,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9573/aidan-rocke","reputation":360,"display_name":"Aidan Rocke","accept_rate":75},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":1,"post_id":21772,"edited":false,"creation_date":1412122483,"comment_id":34459,"body":"Basically because mammals and arthropods evolved separately. If we evolved from a four-legged, fish-like ancestor, then mammals never got to choose how to evolve more efficiently (if it is)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acf97912fe55ce73bdbf18a9608d4bc0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9581,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9581/b1nary-atr0phy","reputation":101,"display_name":"b1nary.atr0phy"},"score":0,"post_id":21772,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1412156203,"comment_id":34473,"body":"@anongoodnurse What does &quot;efficiency&quot; have to do with anything? If the theory that everything evolved from single-celled organisms is correct, then that argument holds little water."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":0,"post_id":21772,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acf97912fe55ce73bdbf18a9608d4bc0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9581,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9581/b1nary-atr0phy","reputation":101,"display_name":"b1nary.atr0phy"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1412169901,"comment_id":34479,"body":"@b1nary.atr0phy - how so?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b7d348e29a14b30e33fcaa0560ceb671?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":9591,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9591/tpg2114","reputation":101,"display_name":"tpg2114"},"score":2,"post_id":21772,"edited":false,"creation_date":1412180441,"comment_id":34488,"body":"Are <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prehensile_tail\" rel=\"nofollow\"