 to 'absorbed colon dose', you use a tissue weighting factor [2]. The tissue weighting factor for the colon is 0.12. So, this means, the average CT Scan results in an 'absorbed colon dose' of ~40 mGy * 0.12 = ~4.8 mGy. <\/p>\n\n<p>I realize there is a different concept of 'effective dose' that calculates risk of cancer based on organ type and organ weight scanned. That is not of interest for my calculations.<\/p>\n\n<p>As far as purely 'absorbed dose' of the organs is concerned, is it accurate to say that the the average CT scan has the same effect on a person's organs as it would to someone standing just outside 2500 meters from the epicenter of Hiroshima?<\/p>\n\n<p>[1] <a href=\"http://www.rerf.jp/general/qa_e/qa2.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.rerf.jp/general/qa_e/qa2.html<\/a><br>\n[2] <a href=\"https://www.euronuclear.org/info/encyclopedia/t/tissue-weight-factor.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.euronuclear.org/info/encyclopedia/t/tissue-weight-factor.htm<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":39549,"tags":["dna","cancer","biophysics","radiation"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":63,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1445958251},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/500d7990f4d8c083fac65cfb0514d992?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19587/bryant-keirns","reputation":6,"display_name":"Bryant Keirns"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":0,"post_id":39991,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445985743,"comment_id":67140,"body":"<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3909779/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here&#39;s<\/a> a relevant article with a free full text access. In conclusion, evidence would point to more than just antioxidants!"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39991/what-exactly-are-polyphenols-and-what-benefits-do-they-provide-to-humans","last_activity_date":1445954716,"creation_date":1445954716,"answer_count":0,"title":"What exactly are polyphenols and what benefits do they provide to humans?","body":"<p>I say somewhere that they are antioxidants, but I was wondering if the two terms are synonymous or if that is just one of many things polyphenols can do.<\/p>\n","question_id":39991,"tags":["biochemistry","microbiology","nutrition"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":18,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef02882c90aecde98e920eae0007b5c2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19583,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19583/cubemaker","reputation":93,"display_name":"CubeMaker"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":15,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":39933,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445823789,"comment_id":66977,"body":"I thought ethanol to be pretty polar? More importantly,  I thought higher percentages EtOH caused microorganisms to dehydrate, killing the cells, but conserving the viable spores of spore-bearing bugs?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"post_id":39933,"reply_to_user"