ionization, but most organic compounds do not dissolve appreciably in water. They usually dissolve, however, in alcohols, and quite often mixed solvents are used. <strong>Methanol - water<\/strong> and <strong>ethanol - water<\/strong> are common mixed solvents for nucleophilic substitution reactions.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Dielectric Constants<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Water - 80<\/li>\n<li>Methanol - 33<\/li>\n<li>Ethanol - 24<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>-Organic Chemistry 11E T.W. Graham Solomons et.al.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>Note<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Dexter's<\/strong> answer provides experimental evidence for why 70% ethanol is used. My answer is based on my experience and understanding and the concentration that I have used in the lab. I would add that 70% was likely chosen as a balance between cost and effectiveness. If you are a little off on mixing the solution from 95% Ethanol stock, then you are still at a bactericidal level, where as if you err at 60% concentration, you could start to let a few bacteria survive.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>70% ethanol is still flammable and should be handled with care. The issue with ethanol greater than 98% pure is that the only way to distill the last 2% of water out is to add <strong>benzene<\/strong>, and benzene is a known carcinogen. There will always be trace amounts of benzene in 100% reagent grade ethanol.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39933,"question_id":39931,"up_vote_count":15,"last_edit_date":1445826378},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0la1I.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4833,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4833/dexter","reputation":1808,"display_name":"Dexter"},"score":11,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":2,"post_id":39934,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445799913,"comment_id":66963,"body":"I think that you need to explain how to interpret the figure you added. What do the pluses and minuses indicate. Does in mean that S. pyogenes survives in 50% for 20s but all are dead by 30s? Do the minuses mean that all bacterium were dead at that time point?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0la1I.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4833,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4833/dexter","reputation":1808,"display_name":"Dexter"},"score":0,"post_id":39934,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1445800509,"comment_id":66964,"body":"Original paper says &quot;+&quot; sign indicates growth of test organism, &quot;-&quot; sign indicates no growth of test organism while &quot;+/-&quot; sign indicates growth in some test and failed in another"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":39934,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445804235,"comment_id":66965,"body":"Okay, so then I am not sure how you draw the conclusion that you make in the italicized parentheses. 50% and 100% show some growth given a certain time course (Must have used the concentration, then significantly diluted to stop, spun down the bacteria and plated), where there was no growth seen at any of the time points for 60% to 95%. I think the correct interpretation is that at 50%, the concentration is low enough that S. pyogenes can survive about 20s and still grow while they are actually able to survive better in 100% ethanol (60s), due to it being a lower polarity solution."},{"owner":{"profile_imag