 citrate does not imply proton release. Acidification is by definition release of protons."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3363534a62c163bf91814cd024889dd8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19568,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19568/joel","reputation":118,"display_name":"Joel"},"score":0,"post_id":39861,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445695092,"comment_id":66900,"body":"Of course they are anions . I just gave an example there are many products from cellular respiration that can form acids in many ways and the ATP hydrolysis is not the only way a proton can be sourced. I don&#39;t know where you got that last bit from"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3363534a62c163bf91814cd024889dd8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19568,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19568/joel","reputation":118,"display_name":"Joel"},"score":0,"post_id":39861,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445699827,"comment_id":66909,"body":"It&#39;s not classed as an acid until the proton and the anion have interacted then it is a molecule that can be deprotonated ( an acid)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3363534a62c163bf91814cd024889dd8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19568,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19568/joel","reputation":118,"display_name":"Joel"},"score":0,"post_id":39861,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445700125,"comment_id":66910,"body":"The question asks for a product of cellular respiration that creates an acid when in solution with water. Since H+ can form hydronium with water an example could be a proton or one of many anions."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef69e4c7ba6adf44fc3d17c4bbacec01?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10401,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10401/tanmath","reputation":1620,"display_name":"TanMa