nt biology (which I really don&#39;t) nitrogen fixers should be able to pump Nitrogen to bacteria at their roots that convert it to ammonium, which is a cation and nitrite which is an anion. Add some water and you probably have enough of an electrolyte to generate a current of electrons, though how much and if it is efficient enough to charge anything, I don&#39;t know."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":39913,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445842022,"comment_id":67009,"body":"The question in its entirety sounds like off-topic. I suggest that you can break down the question into subquestions which can individually be on-topic in either physics, chemistry or biology. For biology, your question should be on the lines of <i>whether soil bacteria can create electrochemical potentials of the order of 100mV<\/i>. Note that even this is a broad question because this all depends on soil type, temperature, mineral/water content and the microbiota."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":39922,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445826037,"comment_id":66980,"body":"Can you cite the claim that the product is in fact a microbial fuel cell?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com